<h1>Keep on learning! Here's some ways to do it.</h1>
<h2>You attended a RailsBridge workshop! That&#8217;s wonderful! Wondering what to do next?</h2>
<ul>
<li>Pick your next project: a tutorial, a class, or building your own app. The main thing: GET STARTED!</li>
<li>Keep in touch with the people you connected with at your workshop. Coding with other people around is really motivating, plus you get to help each other solve trickier stuff.</li>
<li>Come back to another workshop as a student, TA, or teacher. You will definitely learn more, and teaching is a really great way to learn, too. (For those who are new to this: you&#8217;ll be prepared to TA sooner than you think, so don&#8217;t be shy! We need you!)</li>
</ul>
<h3>Resources for you</h3>
<p>There are too many wonderful resources to count, but we&#8217;ve gathered a few of our favorites here.</p>
<h4>Background</h4>
<ul>
<li><a href="http://railsapps.github.io/what-is-ruby-rails.html" target="_blank">What is Ruby on Rails?</a> — in-depth primer introduces basic concepts and explains why Ruby on Rails is popular</li>
</ul>

<h4>Want to learn more Ruby?</h4>
<ul>
<li>Our <a href="http://docs.railsbridge.org/workshop/ruby_for_beginners">Ruby Programming for Beginners</a> curriculum — includes project exercises</li>
<li><a href="http://rubymonk.com/">Ruby Monk</a> — Ruby lessons &amp; tutorials.</li>
<li>Sarah Allen&#8217;s &amp; Alex Chaffee&#8217;s <a href="http://testfirst.org/">TestFirst.org</a> — learn Ruby or JavaScript the test-driven way.</li>
<li><a href="http://rubykoans.com/">Ruby Koans</a> —  a lovely interactive way to test what you know about Ruby so far.</li>
<li><a href="http://ruby.learncodethehardway.org/">Learn Ruby the Hard Way</a> — a Ruby port of Zed Shaw&#8217;s introductory programming tutorial Learn Python the Hard Way.</li>
<li><a title="Code Like This Lessons" href="http://codelikethis.com/lessons" target="_blank">Code Like This (Ruby)</a> &#8211; slides and videos teaching Ruby, linked to <a title="Learn Ruby Test First" href="http://testfirst.org/learn_ruby" target="_blank">TestFirst Labs</a></li>
</ul>
<h4>These Ruby books will knock your socks off:</h4>
<ul>
<li>Chris Pine&#8217;s <a href="http://www.amazon.com/dp/0976694042/ref=nosim?tag=rubydocorg-20&amp;linkCode=sb1&amp;camp=212353&amp;creative=380549">Learn to Program</a> — explains Ruby from the very beginning; includes great challenges &amp; exercises.</li>
<li><a href="http://www.amazon.com/Programming-Ruby-1-9-Pragmatic-Programmers/dp/1934356085">Programming Ruby</a> (a.k.a &#8220;The Pickaxe Book&#8221;) — a comprehensive reference of the Ruby language. A good second or third book on Ruby.</li>
<li><a href="http://www.amazon.com/Eloquent-Addison-Wesley-Professional-Series-ebook/dp/B004MMEJ36">Eloquent Ruby</a> — focuses on writing idiomatic Ruby rather than programming skills or concepts.</li>
</ul>
